{"summary":"All three amendments are technically valid. fr-12-cda1336a and fr-12-cf3e1d18 describe the same reachable terminal-replay `plan_hash` mutation from different angles, while fr-12-589cc81f independently identifies that journal repair is still not forward-compatible across unknown detail fields.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-12-cda1336a","decision":"accept","rationale":"`safe_plan_hash_backfill()` only checks `entry.outcome.is_terminal()` in the `snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation == None` branch. In the `Some(creation_hash)` branch it will still write `entry.plan_hash = Some(creation_hash.clone())` when the current snapshot matches, even for terminal rows. Because `update_task_run()` calls this helper in the terminal replay path, a finalized entry with `plan_hash = None` can be mutated during replay. The proposed guard and regression test are correct."},{"amendment_id":"fr-12-589cc81f","decision":"accept","rationale":"`StartJournalDetails` and `CompletionJournalDetails` still use `#[serde(deny_unknown_fields)]`, and their `parse()` helpers return `None` on unknown fields. In `append_event_if_missing()`, that parse failure blocks in-place repair and falls through to appending a new event, so rollback or older-binary reads of newer journal rows remain non-repairable and can duplicate entries. The merge path also still depends on generic `json_fill_none()` plus manually maintained conflict checks, which does not enforce explicit field-by-field merge semantics for future fields."},{"amendment_id":"fr-12-cf3e1d18","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a valid reachability proof of the terminal replay bug. `TaskRunEntry::merge_attempt_entries()` can propagate `snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation` onto the replay target, and `update_task_run()` still invokes `safe_plan_hash_backfill()` after it has determined the row is already terminal. Since the helper's `Some(creation_hash)` branch lacks a terminal guard, replaying a finalized row with `plan_hash = None` can synthesize a `plan_hash`. It overlaps with fr-12-cda1336a but correctly documents the full end-to-end path."}]}